On the most anticipated for several years, meeting the heads of the Federal Reserve will spend two days this week for 27-футовым table of Honduran mahogany, deciding whether it is time to raise a key interest rate for the first time in almost ten years.
At one end of the richly decorated rooms for meetings height two floors above them will wall the image of the United States.
This map is a reminder that Federal Reserve Chairman Janet L. Yellen and her colleagues must put the economic interests of the country above all others.
The central Bank has received a double assignment from Congress: maximize employment in the United States and maintain stable prices here.
But since the Great Recession, the heads of the Federal system acknowledged that there is a third order: financial stability.
And this is the third order may prove to be an unknown factor in the almost unprecedented decision that will declare on Thursday about whether the U.S. economy is ready to break away from the stimulus, which is almost zero short-term interest rate since the end of 2008.
Even though most of the data show strong growth in the economy, the recent turmoil in world financial markets may hold the already cautious leaders of the Federal system from adding volatility by raising the base federal funds rate - even just a quarter of a percentage point.
"Obviously, the labor market and inflation will be the first and most important issue," said Lindsey M., chief economist at brokerage company & Co.
"But I think if they were looking for a reason not to raise rates, the increased uncertainty around the world market is enough to give them an excuse to wait further," she said.
There is no consensus about what to do in the Federal Reserve system, which, in itself, provokes financial market fluctuations.
Roughly half of economists recently polled by Bloomberg had forecast a rise in interest rates this week.
Financial markets, however, expect the Fed to refrain from it, while a key indicator shows only about 30-процентную likelihood of rapid recovery.
This could lead to a fall in the stock market if the Fed raises rates, provided that those who make decisions, will cushion the blow to the promise that the next increase will not soon.
On Tuesday, the Dow rose 228.89 points, or 1.4 percent, to 16 599.85.
The rise was driven by expectations that the faces that define the strategy of the Federal System will leave rates this week, "said John, Chief economist of Moody's Capital Markets Research group.
"It will be a surprise if the Fed raise rates at this time," he said.
If the leadership of the Federal Reserve system will, they have far to go in asserting its strategy to keep financial markets in their hands, that they do not. "
Other experts argued that raising rates would calm financial markets, as it should remove uncertainty about how the Fed will act.
Just a month ago the Federal system seems to have tended to raise the rate by 0.25 percent this month, making the first little tiny step in a slow tightening of financial conditions that could confirm the strength of the U.S. recovery.
Yellen said in the spring and early summer that it expects to raise rates this year, despite complaints by liberals that need more economic progress.
Although the emergence of new jobs in August slowed, labor market growth was stable this year.
The unemployment rate fell to 5.1 percent last month, the lowest rate in more than seven years, and almost on a level that considered full employment in the Federal system.
Wage growth shows signs of accelerating.
And while inflation continues to be below the central bank target annual rate of 2%, the leadership of the Federal System announced that a key reason was the temporary effect of a sharp fall in oil prices.
"The economy can cope with higher rates, and needs them, taking into account the reduction in the labour market," said Ian, Chief economist at Pantheon Macroeconomics.
But financial markets around the world began to shake at the end of last month, after China devaluing its currency.
The Dow Jones Industrial average fell as much as 16% relative to a record high in May, as investors feared that a slowing Chinese economy could drag on global growth.
The market partly restored its position this month, and the Dow Jones Industrial Average is now about 10% below the high May value.
For the leadership of the Federal Reserve System market resentment additionally complicates the difficult calculations of the term to raise interest rates.
"In the absence of information about what happened in the financial markets and the news about the weakness of the Chinese economy in the last few weeks they would have started tightening the screws at this meeting," said Stephen D., senior researcher at the UCLA Center for Real Estate and a former member of the Federal Reserve system.
Now, he predicted, they will wait at least a month to get more control over the consequences.
"There is a big uncertainty in what might be the consequences for the American economy, and they have almost no reliable data after recent events in China," said.
The health of the global economy is not the main concern of the Federal System, and technically it should not be taken into account when making these decisions.
But essentially the Fed has become the global financial power.
The influence of the Central Bank in recent years has been enormous.
One only hint from the then chairman Ben S. Bernanke in 2013 that the Federal Reserve could "stifle" its monetary expansion, sparked turmoil on markets around the world.
In a world where markets and economies increasingly intertwine with each other, one would expect that the leaders of the Federal Reserve system will not only monitor the development of events everywhere, but to consult with representatives of the other Central banks and experts to better understand the global economy.
Their decision-making process is an art rather than a science, "said Zachary, Head of Inc. - a company that is engaged in global wealth management strategies.
Jeffrey Laquer, President of the Federal Reserve Bank of Richmond, Virginia, said this month that "there have been cases in the history of the Federal Reserve system over-reacting to the movement of the financial market, which does not seem to be related to economic fundamentals."
Laquer, an influential voting member of the Federal Open Market Committee, who pressed for raising rates, as an example of led solutions acquires.
The financial crisis in Asia has led to a Federal system has reduced its base rate at 0.75 percent over three sessions, despite limited identifiable implications for growth in the United States, "said Laquer.
A year later, the heads of the Federal System abolished these cuts.
The Federal Reserve system should be put in the first place only care about stability in times of great crises, such as the collapse of the market in 2008, "said Adam S. Posen, a former member of the Committee for Setting interest rates at the Bank of England.
The latest panic is not close to that level, he said.
"You would certainly not want to be in a situation where you fear growth rates due to the fact that markets are experiencing shock," said Posen, President of the Washington-based Peterson Institute for International economics.
The law on the Federal Reserve still has a dual mandate and mentions financial stability, and until that changes, I don't think they should be ahead of events.
