Obesity surgery can help diabetics with obesity
Favorable effect after obesity surgery in people with obesity, type 2 diabetes sufferers can last for at least five years, according to a new study.
Now, however, it is still too early to assert that diabetics with slight obesity live longer after surgery for obesity than those who receive treatment.
"Mortality statistics is not immediately," said Dr. Robin Blackstone, an expert on obesity Surgery, who wrote about a new study in the column of the editor of JAMA Surgery.
Obesity surgery, or bariatric surgery, uses different methods to reduce the size of the stomach.
They reduce the sense of hunger and restrict the ability to metabolize food.
For several years, bariatric surgery has proved its effectiveness for treating type 2 diabetes, but the basic studies were conducted among people with obesity, having a body mass index (BMI) of 35 or higher.
BMI, a measure of weight relative to growth, is considered normal at value from 18.5 to 24.9.
A BMI of 25 or above suggests that humans have overweight and people with a BMI above 30 are considered people with obesity.
You can calculate your BMI here: 1.usa.gov / 1d0zqdv.
For the new study, researchers from Taiwan General Hospital used data collected from 2007 to compare the two types of bariatric surgery - gastric bypass and sock, with medical treatment for type 2 diabetes in people with low obesity.
The average BMI of those who underwent surgery, dropped from 31 to 24.5 at the end of the fifth year of their participation in the study.
At the same time, the BMI of those who received treatment for diabetes, remains approximately at the level of 29.
Among those who underwent the operation completely cured of diabetes by 36%, and partly - 28%.
In the group who had received medical treatment, for comparison, the complete cure of diabetes was only 1%, and partial - only about 2%.
Additionally, rates of blood pressure, triglycerides and "bad" LDL cholesterol "in general were better in the surgical group," the authors say.
The researchers also monitored the а1с hemoglobin levels in the blood that reflect the blood sugar levels in the dynamics.
Hemoglobin A1c test better hold below 7%, the researchers write.
After surgery, the average hemoglobin A1c test levels decreased from about 9% to around 6%.
In a therapeutic group, however, he remained stable at around 8%.
But the best indicators of control at good levels of hemoglobin A1c test not reduced mortality rates for five years, according to the leader of the Research, Dr. Su and colleagues.
The research team also compared the average results of two types of surgical treatment.
For the fifth year, in comparison with the group, the bypass group lost more weight (18.7 kg versus 14.2 kg), achieved a greater reduction in BMI (7.4 vs. 5.1) and hemoglobin А1с (3.1% vs. 2.1%), and was closer to full remission of diabetes (46.9% vs. 16.7%).
Although the new study does not demonstrate the benefits of surgical method in terms of life expectancy after five years, according to the results of the study confirm there are people with overweight in Sweden that surgical treatment really leads to increased life expectancy, according to Blackstone of the College of Medicine in Phoenix, the University of Arizona.
According to Swedish studies for people with obesity who have chosen intervention, the likelihood of dying for 15 years was about 29% lower compared to the group that used more traditional methods.
Although the new study showed no increase in life expectancy, Blackstone noted that it is encouraging people with a BMI below 35 interested in such a procedure.
"Here is a very important report, because it stated that such surgery safely in the group with low BMI, where there is no increased risk of death or kidney disease," she said.
Blackstone added that people and their doctors must begin to seriously treat weight as soon as a patient's BMI falls into the range between 27 and 30.
"I think we are waiting too long to get people to take this seriously," she said.
